			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: &quot;DieselGate&quot; possible huge fall of VW Group?
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1841307">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Deabn</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1841258#post1841258" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Related: GM's faulty ignition switches (100+ fatalities, but no criminal indictments?), Toyota's faulty accelerators.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>I know a lot of people won't understand the difference, but the GM and Toyota issues were bad engineering, and a lack of effort in response. They were not deliberate attempts to get people killed.<br />
<br />
The VW issue is different. The VW chip is built specifically to commit fraud. That's a different animal and has a different reaction especially within the engineering community. Engineers can tolerate being bad at the job. The job is fucking hard. But they do not tolerate being intentionally untruthful. This has more to do with the lie and less to do with the actual consequences.<br />
<br />
Building a device to deliberately mislead people into buying your car is pretty much the highest order of evil in commercial engineering. It breaks the trust of the public and the unspoken understanding that engineers are here to help reach the next thing technologically.<br />
<br />
This is up there with when the oil companies lied about lead poisoning.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
